'''Maxine Fensom''' (born 30 August 1958) is an Australian [[entrepreneur]] well known in the adult industry for founding a number of strip clubs, strippers’ agencies, themed events and adult online stores. She also established the annual [[Australian Adult Industry Awards]] in 2001 to recognise achievements in the adult industry as well as the national Miss Erotica and Miss Dream Girl pageants.

== Early life & education ==
Maxine was born on 30 August 1958 in Brisbane, Australia. Moving to Melbourne at the age of two, Maxine was educated at Camberwell High School and Brinsley Road Free School in Camberwell and had a modest upbringing, the only child of a single mother. She trained as a psychiatric nurse at [[Swinburne Technical College]], but eventually her passion for dancing and acting led her to setting up a promotional dance troupe, which performed around Melbourne successfully for a number of years. Maxine also acted on television,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0271994/|title=Maxine Fensom|website=IMDb|access-date=2016-08-03}}</ref> appearing in various episodes as “Bouncy Miss” in the acclaimed [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] miniseries “[[The Damnation of Harvey McHugh]]”. She has also had a biography written about her life as the most recognisable female face in the adult industry.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Maxine stripped naked : tales from the sex industry|last=Leigh|first=Jeanette|publisher=Pennon Publishing|year=2004|isbn=|location=Essendon|pages=|via=}}</ref>

== Career ==

Maxine currently operates a [[Strip club|gentlemen’s club]] in the suburb of [[Brunswick, Victoria|Brunswick]] in Melbourne. Other businesses she operates include event agencies, a topless bar, an adult merchandise online store, a concierge service and adult party services.

Her career in the adult industry began as after her three-year stint on the daily horoscope segment of Channel Nine’s In Melbourne Today show ended. Hosting bucks parties and private functions, Maxine’s business grew exponentially, taking on corporate customers<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/01/17/1073878082741.html|title=Naked Ambition|last=Halliday|first=Claire|date=17 January 2004|work=|access-date=|via=The Age}}</ref> and establishing a business headquarters with the support of high-profile porn publisher [[Larry Flynt]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/hustle-strips-away-hassle-for-madam/2007/12/15/1197568332288.html|title=Hustle Strips Away Hassle For Madam|last=Elder|first=John|date=16 December 2007|work=|access-date=|via=The Age}}</ref> As a prominent female face in the male-dominated adult and sex industry, Maxine has had her fair share of challenges, including social media bullying.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/technology/technology-news/disliking-maxine-sex-industry-feud-hits-facebook-20130320-2ggyi.html|title=Disliking Maxine: sex industry feud hits Facebook|last=Elder|first=John|date=21 March 2013|work=|access-date=|via=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> Maxine is a strong supporter of legalised brothels, more regulations around employment in the sex industry and increased sentences for perpetrators of violent crime, running as an independent candidate in [[Electoral results for the district of Melbourne|Victorian state elections in 2002 and 2010]].

