'''Rynella''' is an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in [[Iberia Parish, Louisiana]], United States that consists of a few residential dwellings and a [[volunteer fire department]] along Highway 329 (also known as the [[Avery Island]] Highway). The name ''Rynella'' allegedly is a portmanteau deriving from the last two letters of the first names of three local women, Rosema''RY'', Pauli''NE'', and Lei''LA'' McIlhenny (someone eventually adding an extra L to the resulting word). They were daughters of [[Edward Avery McIlhenny]], a noted Louisiana [[conservation movement|conservationist]] who presided over [[McIlhenny Company]], maker of [[Tabasco sauce|Tabasco]] brand pepper sauce at nearby Avery Island.<ref>Shane K. Bernard, ''Tabasco: An Illustrated History'' (Avery Island, La.: McIlhenny Company, 2007).</ref>  (At one time McIlhenny operated a general store at Rynella and he owned much of the land that now comprises and surrounds the community.)

